# Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)

Capture decisions that are hard to reverse, span multiple modules, or
encode opinion that future contributors might second-guess.

## When to write one

| Trigger | ADR? |
|---|---|
| Adding a new top-level directory or file outside the map in `AGENTS.md` | yes |
| Changing the calibration version contract | yes |
| Choosing between two equally valid libraries (e.g. Sherpa vs PyXspec) | yes |
| Hard-pinning a default (cosmology, extinction model, aperture) | yes |
| Bumping the Python minimum version | yes |
| Adding a new public dataclass that other modules will import | yes |
| Renaming an exported symbol | yes |
| Refactoring within a single file | no |
| Adding a private helper | no |
| Fixing a bug without API change | no |

## Naming

`docs/adr/ADR-NNNN-short-kebab-title.md`, sequentially numbered.

## Template

```markdown
# ADR-NNNN — Title

**Status.** Proposed | Accepted | Superseded by ADR-MMMM | Deprecated.

## Context
What problem are we solving? Why does it matter? What constraints exist?

## Decision
The choice in one or two sentences.

## Consequences
- What becomes easy.
- What becomes harder.
- What we lose.
- Migration path, if any.

## Alternatives considered
- Alternative A — why rejected.
- Alternative B — why rejected.

## References
- Links to related PRs, papers, prior art.
```

## Existing ADRs

See `PHASE2_PLAN.md §8` for the seed list (ADR-0001 .. ADR-0005). New ADRs
follow the next available number.

## Lifecycle

- "Proposed" goes into the repo on the PR that proposes it.
- "Accepted" is set when the PR merges.
- "Superseded" is set by a later ADR that replaces it; both files stay in
  the repo. Never delete an ADR.
